{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01TMDokWZYB16ab3tAz2qRw1","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"There's a failing test: \"filters INGREDIENTS section label so real ALL_CAPS title wins\". \n\nThe test:\n```typescript\nit(\"filters INGREDIENTS section label so real ALL_CAPS title wins\", async () => {\n  const embed = createMockEmbed([\"mozzarella sticks\"], []);\n  const text = \"INGREDIENTS\\nMOZZARELLA STICKS\\n- 2 tbsp sugar\";\n  const result = await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(text, embed);\n  expect(result).toBe(\"MOZZARELLA STICKS\");\n\n\n});\n```\n\nThe result is `\"INGREDIENTS MOZZARELLA STICKS\"` instead of `\"MOZZARELLA STICKS\"`, which means `INGREDIENTS` isn't being filtered out by `isSectionLabel`. I'm tracing through the `passesHardFilters` function to see why it's not catching this...\n\nExamining the hard filters...\n\nChecking the `isSectionLabel` function...\n\nI'm defining a helper that normalizes text by trimming whitespace and removing trailing colons or periods, then checking if it matches known section labels like \"ingredients\". So when \"INGREDIENTS\" gets passed through, it should normalize to \"ingredients\" and return true, which means `passesHardFilters` should reject it. But the test result shows \"INGREDIENTS MOZZARELLA STICKS\" is getting through, which suggests the issue is that this multi-line string isn't being caught by the hard filters—the function is probably only checking the first line or the entire concatenated string isn't matching the section label check. embed(\"INGREDIENTS MOZZARELLA STICKS\")` → lower is \"ingredients mozzarella sticks\", which contains \"mozzarella sticks\" → isTitle = true → [0.9, 0.1, 0]\n- `embed(\"MOZZARELLA STICKS\")` → lower is \"mozzarella sticks\", which contains \"mozzarella sticks\" → isTitle = true → [0.9, 0.1, 0]\n\nBoth get the same rawScore = titleSim - max(headerSim, noiseSim) = (dot product with [1,0,0]) - max(dot product with [0,1,0], dot product with [0,0,1])\n\nFor [0.9, 0.1, 0]:\n- titleSim = cos([0.9,0.1,0],\n\nCalculating the embedding scores for both candidates to see how they compare in the ranking. So the first candidate gets a position factor boost of 1.12 with an all-caps bonus, while the second one stays at 1.0 since its relative position of 0.5 doesn't qualify for the bonus. Let me recalculate the position factor more carefully by looking at the actual line structure—there are three lines total, so I need to verify how the relative positioning works for each match. Now I'm calculating the final scores for both candidates: \"INGREDIENTS MOZZARELLA STICKS\" scores around 1.069 while \"MOZZARELLA STICKS\" comes in at 0.998, so both clear the threshold. But then the deduplication logic kicks in—since \"MOZZARELLA STICKS\" is a substring of the longer version, it should remove the shorter one to keep the more focused result.\n\nWait, let me trace through the actual filter logic here. It removes an item if there's another item that contains it as a substring and is longer. So \"INGREDIENTS MOZZARELLA STICKS\" would get filtered out because \"MOZZARELLA STICKS\" is contained within it and is shorter, leaving just the more concise match.\n\nBut the test is showing \"INGREDIENTS MOZZARELLA STICKS\" survived, which means either \"MOZZARELLA STICKS\" didn't make it through the earlier filters, or I'm misunderstanding the dedup logic. Let me check if `looksLikeIngredient` is catching \"MOZZARELLA STICKS\" and filtering it out before dedup even runs. Now I'm checking if \"MOZZARELLA STICKS\" passes the garbled text filter by counting its vowels—it has 5 vowels out of 16 letters, giving a ratio of about 0.31, which falls within the acceptable range, so it's not flagged as garbled.\n\nWait, I need to verify that `isSectionLabel` is working correctly for \"INGREDIENTS\"—it normalizes to lowercase and checks against the section labels set, which should contain it. But if \"INGREDIENTS\" alone gets filtered out while \"INGREDIENTS MOZZARELLA STICKS\" passes, that suggests the two-line join isn't being normalized the same way.\n\nThe dedup logic should catch \"INGREDIENTS MOZZARELLA STICKS\" as a superset of \"MOZZARELLA STICKS\" and remove it, but the test shows it's actually being returned. I'm wondering if the issue is in how `isStructuralHeading` validates candidates—maybe it's only accepting items with multiple words where each word meets certain criteria.\n\nLet me trace through the validation for \"INGREDIENTS MOZZARELLA STICKS\": it's all caps, has 3 words, and each word has enough alphabetic characters to pass the filter. So it would qualify as a structural heading.\n\nNow checking \"MOZZARELLA STICKS\" the same way—it's also all caps with 2 words, and both pass the character length requirement, so it's structural too. Since they embed to the same score, the tiebreaker logic would kick in to pick between them.\n\nWhen there's a tie, the single-line version wins, so \"MOZZARELLA STICKS\" becomes the base heading. Next I'm looking for the first structural heading that starts with this base text followed by a special character like a slash or ampersand.\n\n\"INGREDIENTS MOZZARELLA STICKS\" doesn't match because it starts with \"ingredients\", not \"mozzarella sticks\", so the base heading itself becomes the first structural heading. In the bonus pass, only \"MOZZARELLA STICKS\" gets the structural bonus, giving it a final score of 0.883.\n\nNow I'm calculating the threshold scores: both candidates get 0.963 after adding the all-caps bonus, which sets the threshold at around 0.67.\n\nSince both scores exceed this threshold, they both pass the initial filter. Then I'm applying deduplication logic that removes any result if a shorter version of it already exists in the results—so \"mozzarella sticks\" would eliminate \"ingredients mozzarella sticks\" since it's a substring.\n\nWriting dedup filter... the dedup step) should catch this. Let me trace through what's happening more carefully—maybe the issue is that \"INGREDIENTS MOZZARELLA STICKS\" is somehow passing the dedup filter when it shouldn't be, or perhaps the selected list has a different state than I'm assuming. I'm tracing through the logic more carefully now. The filter removes candidates that are word-boundary prefixes of \"MOZZARELLA STICKS\", so \"INGREDIENTS MOZZARELLA STICKS\" survives since it's not a prefix. Then the continuation join check doesn't filter it out either since \"MOZZARELLA STICKS\" doesn't start with a continuation character. Moving into the pre-dedup step where section headers get removed... After deduplication, \"MOZZARELLA STICKS\" should remain while \"INGREDIENTS MOZZARELLA STICKS\" gets filtered out as a substring. But the test is showing the opposite result, which means I need to look more carefully at how `buildCandidates` actually constructs these merged lines — it seems to be using the raw text rather than the filtered candidates.\n\nWhen I trace through `passesHardFilters` for \"INGREDIENTS MOZZARELLA STICKS\", it passes all the checks: it's not too short or long, doesn't match ingredient patterns, has no numbers or metadata markers, and isn't garbled despite being all caps with decent vowel distribution.\n\nNow I'm realizing the issue might be with the dedup logic itself. If \"MOZZARELLA STICKS\" has position 1 and should be removed as a substring of the 2-line join, it would only happen if \"MOZZARELLA STICKS\" is already in the selected list when dedup runs. But what if it's not there yet, or what if the position tracking is causing it to be skipped?\n\nLet me trace through the `firstStructuralHeading` logic more carefully—it's looking for a structural heading that starts with the base heading text followed by specific punctuation, and I think that's where the continuation join is being created. I'm filtering out candidates where the first structural heading starts with their text plus a space, so \"INGREDIENTS MOZZARELLA STICKS\" stays because \"mozzarella sticks\" doesn't start with \"ingredients mozzarella sticks \", while \"MOZZARELLA STICKS\" passes as the heading itself—but I'm realizing this filter might not be working as intended.\n\nNow I'm looking at the join protection logic, which identifies multi-line joins that survived the filtering. Since \"INGREDIENTS MOZZARELLA STICKS\" is a 2-line join, it gets flagged, and then I'm checking whether any single-line candidates are prefixes of these surviving joins so I can remove them. I'm walking through a specific example with \"MOZZARELLA STICKS\" to verify the filtering logic—checking whether it gets removed as a prefix or suffix of a join, and confirming it survives this stage before moving into the deduplication phase.\n\nNow I'm examining the next candidate at position 1, which is \"- 2 tbsp sugar\". The ingredient detection recognizes \"tbsp\" as a measurement pattern, so it's flagged as an ingredient. Since this follows an ingredient and there's a longer parent candidate (\"INGREDIENTS MOZZARELLA STICKS\") that contains the current text, I need to evaluate whether this should be deduplicated.\n\nThe issue is that \"MOZZARELLA STICKS\" gets removed because it's all caps, followed by an ingredient line, and has a longer parent candidate containing it. This leaves only the combined \"INGREDIENTS MOZZARELLA STICKS\" in the selected results, which then fails the multi-title guard check since there's only one all-caps entry.\n\nThe real problem is that \"INGREDIENTS MOZZARELLA STICKS\" shouldn't be a candidate in the first place—it's a spurious two-line join that's contaminating the pool. The cleanest fix would be to prevent it from passing the hard filters so it never becomes an option to compare against.\n\nI can improve the `isSectionLabel` check to catch not just exact matches but also lines that start with a known section label followed by a space, which would filter out these problematic joins at the source.\n\nEnhancing the section label detection...\n\nNow I'm wondering if this could create false positives—what if a recipe title legitimately starts with a word that happens to be in the section labels list? I need to think through whether that's actually a realistic concern.\n\nActually, I think the real issue is that I'm trying to filter based on prefix matching, which is too broad. A better approach might be to check whether the first line of a potential join would have been filtered as a section label before combining them, rather than checking the combined result. The issue is that `passesHardFilters` on the joined text returns true because the section label check only examines the full string, not the individual components. So I need to add a check: when building multi-line joins, if the first line itself would fail `passesHardFilters` (like a section label), don't create a join starting from it, since there might be other reasons beyond section labels that should prevent a line from being a join starter. part of a valid join. For example, a line that's too short alone might be meaningful as part of a join. Actually looking at the existing code, the joins are created regardless of whether the individual lines pass - only the joined result is checked.\n\nA simpler fix would be to check if the first line is a section label before creating the join, which would prevent things like \"INGREDIENTS MOZZARELLA STICKS\" from being generated as candidates. The `isSectionLabel` function is already defined earlier in the file around line 106, and `buildCandidates` is defined later around line 213, so I can use it there. I should add this check to the 2-line and 3-line join creation logic.\n\nThis is a targeted approach that stops problematic joins at the source without affecting existing tests, since they all start with valid non-section-label lines anyway. Looking at the actual code, I see the SECTION_LABELS set includes multi-word Polish entries like \"sposób przygotowania\" and \"sposób wykonania\", but there are no \"for the...\" style entries—those were only in the plan, not the implementation.\n\nThe real problem is that if I add a check to prevent joins from starting with section labels, then a title like \"Sos Pomidorowy\" would get split into separate lines \"Sos\" and \"Pomidorowy\", and the join wouldn't be created since \"Sos\" itself is flagged as a section label. But \"Sos\" alone also wouldn't pass the hard filters anyway because `isSectionLabel(\"Sos\")` returns true—it normalizes to \"sos\" which is in SECTION_LABELS.\n\nThe key insight is that this check only prevents joins from starting with section labels; a complete line like \"Sos Pomidorowy\" would still pass the hard filters since the full text isn't in SECTION_LABELS. So the extraction would work fine as long as the title appears as a single line.\n\nI'm going to go with modifying `buildCandidates` to skip joins that start with section labels—it's the most targeted fix and doesn't change how section detection works globally. I see the issue now—when we join \"INGREDIENTS\" with \"MOZZARELLA STICKS\", the combined text doesn't match our section labels because it normalizes to something we don't recognize. The safest approach is to prevent joins from starting with lines that are already section labels themselves, so I'll add that check in `buildCandidates` before creating the 2-line and 3-line joins.\n\nImplementing the fix now.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3919,"cache_read_input_tokens":44376,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3919},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e82029a8-8ec1-4638-ae16-802ee09be476","uuid":"055aac0a-96b2-4495-acfe-687be88b8283"}
